commit.message:
ghub--graphql-prepare-query: Use smallest pagination setting

Previously if pagination was explicitly specified for a certain edge,
then that was used unconditionally, even if it happened to be larger
than the "maximum" specified for "all" edges, using the PAGINATE
argument or `ghub-graphql-items-per-request' variable.

Now, if a caller specifies PAGINATE or the user lowers
`ghub-graphql-items-per-request', they can be sure that that is always
respected.

commit.message:
ghub--graphql-vacuum: Add PAGINATE argument

Add the same argument to internal caller of that function.  Store
the value in the PAGINATE slot of the request object, and finally
put it in action in `ghub--graphql-prepare-query'.

Previously a caller had to pass this information by let-binding
`ghub-graphql-items-per-request', if it did not want to use the
global default value.

Also see previous commit.

commit.message:
No longer prepare GraphQL queries prematurely

`ghub--graphql-vacuum' calls
  `ghub--graphql-retrieve' calls
    `ghub--graphql-prepare-query'
      - calls `ghub--graphql-narrow-query'
        Which doesn't do anything for this first request because
        LINEAGE is nil.
      - and prepares the QUERY for `gsexp-encode'

All `ghub-fetch-*' functions (except `ghub-fetch-repository') first
need to narrow the value of the `ghub-fetch-repository' variable to the
part they are interested in.  They used `ghub--graphql-narrow-query',
which means that that function was run twice before even making the
first request.  Until now that wasn't a big issue, the query was not
modified the second time around, but it was a bit wasteful.

The next commit adds a PAGINATE argument to `ghub--graphql-vacuum',
which stores that in a new PAGINATE field slot of the request object.
`ghub--graphql-retrieve' passes the slots value to
`ghub--graphql-prepare-query', which takes it into account when
preparing the query.

Part of what `ghub--graphql-prepare-query' does to the query is to
encode pagination.  This is done in a way that loses information.
[(:edges E)] becomes [(first F)))], where F depends on E and the
pagination information from the request object.  Once F is stored
in the query, E is lost, so calling this function again (with new
pagination information from the object), cannot change the outcome
in the query anymore.

That is very easy to avoid: use `ghub--graphql-narrow-query' for
the early call, avoiding the unnecessary, destructive preparation.

commit.message:
ghub-response-link-relations: Fix for GitLab

They changed the name of the header from `Link' to `link', or maybe
they always did the latter (though I expect this issue would have been
reported a long time ago, if that were the case).

To this day, the section [1] where they documents this header, is name
"Pagination `Link' header" (with `Link' using code syntax), which is
misleading, especially consider that HTTP headers traditionally are
capitalized [2], but in their API it is not (while some others are).

[1]: https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/api/rest/index.html#pagination-link-header
[2]: https://www.iana.org/assignments/http-fields/http-fields.xhtml#field-names
